abstract: “The Loudest Voice,” “Ink” and “Succession” map out the influential world the two men created.
snippet: “The Loudest Voice,” “Ink” and “Succession” map out the influential world the two men created.
lead_paragraph: Roger Ailes (Russell Crowe) begins narrating his own story, Showtime’s “The Loudest Voice,” as he lies dead on the floor. I mean, why wouldn’t he?

abstract: The president outrages the Democratic base daily, but the lawmakers who gave Democrats their House majority remain firm that impeachment is not what their constituents want.
snippet: The president outrages the Democratic base daily, but the lawmakers who gave Democrats their House majority remain firm that impeachment is not what their constituents want.
lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — As a former federal prosecutor, Representative Mikie Sherrill of New Jersey says she relies on evidence, and she needs to see more of it before considering whether to impeach President Trump.

abstract: A handful of companies already dominate the market for digital assistants. The implications for consumer privacy are a serious concern, researchers say.
snippet: A handful of companies already dominate the market for digital assistants. The implications for consumer privacy are a serious concern, researchers say.
lead_paragraph: PALO ALTO, Calif. — It has been almost two decades since Google started to dominate internet search the way Microsoft dominated software for personal computers a generation earlier.

abstract: It was the biggest disaster in the history of the music business — and almost nobody knew. This is the story of the 2008 Universal fire.
snippet: It was the biggest disaster in the history of the music business — and almost nobody knew. This is the story of the 2008 Universal fire.
lead_paragraph: The fire that swept across the backlot of Universal Studios Hollywood on Sunday, June 1, 2008, began early that morning, in New England. At 4:43 a.m., a security guard at the movie studio and theme park saw flames rising from a rooftop on the set known as New England Street, a stretch of quaint Colonial-style buildings where small-town scenes were filmed for motion pictures and television shows. That night, maintenance workers had repaired the roof of a building on the set, using blowtorches to heat asphalt shingles. They finished the job at 3 a.m. and, following protocol, kept watch over the site for another hour to ensure that the shingles had cooled. But the roof remained hot, and some 40 minutes after the workers left, one of the hot spots flared up.

abstract: No single food regimen works for everyone. A new study is the most comprehensive effort yet to understand why.
snippet: No single food regimen works for everyone. A new study is the most comprehensive effort yet to understand why.
lead_paragraph: A decade ago, spurred by the success of the Human Genome Project and the affordability of genetic sequencing, scientists began to explore the promise of “nutrigenomics.” Could personalized nutrition, informed by knowledge of an individual’s DNA, help prevent and even treat diet-related diseases?

abstract: The retired senator Mike Gravel gave two young fans his Twitter password and permission to campaign in his name. It might be a stunt — or the future of politics.
snippet: The retired senator Mike Gravel gave two young fans his Twitter password and permission to campaign in his name. It might be a stunt — or the future of politics.
lead_paragraph: Zach Montellaro, a Politico reporter, reads the Federal Election Commission website like a tabloid. He not only trawls the big, dry database in which presidential candidates register to run; he also reads several smaller aftermarket ones that reformat the filings from the first. On Twitter, he follows F.E.C. bots that tweet out campaign filings as they post. On the night of March 19, he was up late when one such tweet, from @CATargetBot, crossed his feed: “NEW FEC F1 #POTUS Mike Gravel for President Exploratory Committee.”

abstract: From paddleboarding in Colorado to bachata music in Puerto Rico, we asked writers to tell us what makes their beach vacations the best.
snippet: From paddleboarding in Colorado to bachata music in Puerto Rico, we asked writers to tell us what makes their beach vacations the best.
lead_paragraph: Choose any beach vacation town, and you can expect to find a few things — water, sand, probably ice cream, possibly a Ferris wheel. But it takes a little more to make a spot the kind of place that people from the nearest big town and beyond return to summer after summer, sometimes for generations. We chose 25 wildly different destinations around the country — from the comically perfect shore of the Florida Panhandle to Iowan lakeside Americana to the finicky coast of the Pacific Northwest — and asked writers who love them to explain their charms.

abstract: While House Democratic leaders agonize, black voters want President Trump impeached, and their ardor on the subject is driving their representatives.
snippet: While House Democratic leaders agonize, black voters want President Trump impeached, and their ardor on the subject is driving their representatives.
lead_paragraph: PHILADELPHIA — Moments after the special counsel, Robert S. Mueller III, wrapped up his appearance at the Justice Department on Wednesday, Representative Dwight Evans stepped out of his district office in a black working-class neighborhood here to visit with local business owners. They had one question on their minds: Why is President Trump still in office?
